      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on this embedded c++ project for an automotive sensor module and i'm running into a weird issue. the system runs fine for a few hours but then eventually hits an out-of-memory error and crashes. i suspect a memory leak somewhere in the telemetry processing loop. \n\ncan you look at this snippet and tell me how i should systematically go about finding where the deallocation is failing?\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet == nullptr) return;\n\n    // Allocate buffer for processed data\n    float* data_buffer = new float[packet->data_length];\n    \n    for (int i = 0; i < packet->data_length; ++i) {\n        data_buffer[i] = transform_data(packet->raw_values[i]);\n    }\n\n    // Send to telemetry service\n    if (!telemetry_service.send(data_buffer, packet->data_length)) {\n        log_error(\"Telemetry send failed\");\n        // System keeps running but we might have issues here\n    }\n\n    // Update internal state\n    update_system_stats(data_buffer, packet->data_length);\n\n    // TODO: Cleanup buffer?\n}\n```\ni'm not seeing any obvious issues but the heap is definitely creeping up. what's the best way to profile this without blowing the memory budget of the testing rig?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
